    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "discussion",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Discussion",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "While the currency-symbol part of this feature may be useful in certain types of applications, it’s probably more likely that you would tie a particular application to a particular currency (that is, that you would “hard-code” the currency symbol and separators instead of having them dynamically change based on the user’s configuration). The reason for this, of course, is that "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "NSNumberFormatter"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " doesn’t perform currency conversions, it just formats numeric data. You wouldn’t want one user interpreting the value "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "\"56324\""
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " as US currency and another user who’s accessing the same data interpreting it as Japanese currency, simply based on each user’s localization preferences."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
